<subSubSection pageNumber="350" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="350">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="350">Note:</emphasis>
Reveal &amp; al. (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="350">Bartonia</emphasis>
56: 19. 1990) have argued that only part of the Dillenius illustration designated as the 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
by Parks was cited under the supposedly 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“typical”">&quot;typical&quot;</normalizedToken>
part of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
protologue, arguing for restriction of the type to a single leaf. However, this seems unhelpful and recent authors such as Strother (in Daniel, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="350">Fl. Chiapas</emphasis>
5: 73. 1999) and Wagner &amp; Robinson (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="350">Brittonia</emphasis>
53: 557. 2002) follow Parks.
</paragraph>
